n","1200–Male":"1200–Overleden","1200–Female":"1200–Overleden","1170–Male":"1170–Overleden","about 1170":"circa 1170","ABT 1200":"circa 1200","1200":"1200","about 1200":"circa 1200","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","Blaengwrach, Glamorgan, Wales":"Blaengwrach, Glamorgan, Wales","Wales":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Glyn-nedd, Blaen-gwrach, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Blaengwrach, Glamorgan, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Senghennydd cantref, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Senghenydd, Glamorgan, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1170–":"about 1170–Deceased","1182–Female":"1182–Deceased","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1200–Female":"1200–Deceased","1170–Male":"1170–Deceased","about 1170":"about 1170","ABT 1200":"about 1200","1200":"1200","about 1200":"about 1200","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","Blaengwrach, Glamorgan, Wales":"Blaengwrach, Glamorgan, Wales","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Glyn-nedd, Blaen-gwrach, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Blaengwrach, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Senghennydd cantref, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Senghenydd, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gollwyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Irit.","English (Hampshire): from the Old English personal name <i>Goldwine</i>, composed of the elements <i>gold</i> ‘gold’ + <i>wīn</i> ‘friend’.","Americanized form of any of various like-sounding Jewish (Ashkenazic) surnames."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Gollwyn was born about 1170, in Blaengwrach, Glamorgan, Wales. He married Ellyw verch Rhys Gryg in Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 2 daughters. He died in Wales, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1170–":"umbes 1170–Surnud","1182–Female":"1182–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","about 1170":"umbes 1170","ABT 1200":"umbes 1200","1200":"1200","about 1200":"umbes 1200","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","Blaengwrach, Glamorgan, Wales":"Blaengwrach, Glamorgan, Wales","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Glyn-nedd, Blaen-gwrach, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Blaengwrach, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Senghennydd cantref, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Senghenydd, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1170–":"noin 1170–Kuollut","1182–Female":"1182–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1200–Female":"1200–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","about 1170":"no